,Not Recommended,329200,18956331,"Posted: 8 November, 2015",all,Polarizer,"Needs More CowbellAstrayis clearly the result of an energy drink fueled all-nighter. Its story is full of holes, contradictions, and dropped threads. The level design is chaotic and lacks any sense of scale. Other than the odd hidden pressure plate (no spoilers) the puzzles are dull and uninspired and, except for the last one, serve only as a means to move from one level to the next and have nothing to do with the story.  The opening puzzle, which contains a multi-part solution, is the most thought out in the game, though it fostered the expectation that the puzzles would be challenging (they weren’t) and varying (they’re all basically variations on the same thing, other than the final one). The influence of games likeAmnesia: The Dark Descent(mood and wandering monsters, not to mentionthe magic book puzzle), and especially the pseudo-parkour ofHalf Life II(all that box stacking). The final puzzle reminds me a lot ofMetro Last Light(only without the excitement) and Oblivion realms from theElder Scrollsgames. There’s nothing especially original here, and much that is frankly and obviously derivative.The world lacks any kind of human touch. The resources used (lamps, desks, bookcases, etc) are scattered about very sparsely. The result is barren, lifeless, echoing places that you run through looking for the next puzzle piece. You can't hide the lack of detail with fogallof the time! There are bad textures as well as missing textures. It is not conceivable that a mansion in 1909 would have modern galvanized steel air conditioning ductwork that looks like something out of, once again,Half Life IIor any of a number ofDeus Exgames. Don’t get me started on the water puzzles or the doors that mysteriously open (or close) triggered by things you do elsewhere. And hey, what about all those large crates in small rooms that could not possibly have gone through the doors--any of them?On the brighter side, the music seemed appropriately chosen for mood-setting and atmosphere, though the atmosphere loops were highly repetitive.That brings me to the ending, which consists of a final puzzle and a series of cutscenes. Here I threw up my hands. It was like cutting the Gordian knot. Important questions were tossed aside, quest objects were ignored, well trodden game mechanisms went out the window, entirely new and unexplained symbols appeared, and then suddenly it was over. I think I even saw a screenshot from Amnesia, but I can’t be sure. What a mess. Think of the worst head scratcher you’ve ever seen. This is much worse. Adding cowbell wouldn’t make it worse.Finally, the title. Really? I don’t mind so much that ignorant people have pointed out that it looks like “ashtray.” That’s the level of fan we’re dealing with, and that’s okay. I also don’t mind the people who have posted videos in which they prove that they don’t know what the word means by pronouncing it incorrectly--we live in a world in which ignorance is celebrated and correcting people is considered a microaggression--but what I do mind is that there is no discernible connection between the adverb “astray” (as in “Mary’s little lambs have wandered astray and she can’t find them”) and anything in the game whatsoever, on any level. Other than than the fact that I was let astray into buying this mess because it was inexpensive.My recommendation is that you resist the temptation to be led astray into this game. It's just not worth the time."
