76561198028006567,Recommended,329200,19121688,"Posted: 16 November, 2015",all,Phydro,"Caution: contains mild spoilers.Conditionally recommended. The game's strongest points are its atmosphere and setting - using a museum is a great idea that I haven't really seen done in a game like this before, and most of the areas are very pretty and eerie. It's really a fun experience just to go through and see what the developers built, and I wish there was a museum this size and scope in real life.The story, however, is about as cookie-cutter-Cthullian as you can find. There's no variation whatsoever on the standard ""lost artifact brings chaos"" plot, and the character you play as is little more than a camera for you to pilot around - no personality whatsoever. I don't mean his/her personality was written badly, I mean they literally say nothing, think nothing, and have no motive for doing all this except that someone's playing a horror game. The first thing you do is solve a very deadly electrical puzzle, and I can't help but think there is no motivation for anyone to do that so early on, no matter how long the uncle's been missing. There are a few well-written moments that build a bit of suspense and even make you question whether something is real or not, but it passes without much impact. What irks me about it so much is that this game is set in amuseum!One ""based on unusual cultures, legends, and supernatural themes."" There was so much opportunity to build a complex and dreadful mystery between different cultures, historical periods, and mythologies, and all that atmosphere was wasted on fetch quests instead of lore-building. Adding an experienced writer to the team could have done so much for this game.The puzzles are very simplistic. I've seen others compare this to Myst, but I wouldn't even call it close. The hardest thing you'll do is an ""A = weird symbol"" alphabet puzzle. There are enemies of an Amnesia: The Dark Descent variety, but they are quite unthreatening after the first encounter. They won't attack unless you shine a light on them (a creative touch, but it backfired) or are within a foot or two of them. Be aware that this game probably will not give you more than two hours of gameplay at most as a result.As a final note, several elements lead me to question if the devleopers have finished their work on it or not.In the beginning, you seem to be being chased, but it's never addressed again. Also, about midway through, a character in a painting vanishes when your back is turned and knockes over a display in the process. Creepy, but nothing happens in relation to it again. Not sure if I missed something or not.I know I've been hard on this, but in the end, the fact is I did enjoy it, and two hours of extremely well-built environments is not a bad use of $7. I hope the developers revisit this concept with a larger team and more time to invest, because it really could have been so much more. Just be aware that, if you're looking for a really scary experience or challenging puzzles, this game will probably disappoint. But as an intriguing exploration built by only two people, it's a worthy experience."
