76561197975580504,Recommended,329200,18129025,"Posted: 21 September, 2015",all,Mostly Harmless,"Astray is a first-person horror game with gameplay very reminescent of Amnesia: The Dark Descent. It's a microbudget indie game made by only two people, but unlike many such games on Steam it's actually very solidly made and professionally presented. It definitely comes across as a professionally made game, rather than (unlike many first-person horror games on Steam) a programming student project.The game has fully rebindable keys, invert mouse, and decent graphics options, and as far as I've seen the game doesn't have any major bugs or other amateurish weirdness.It's a fairly short game (I finished it in a little over 2 hours, and that was on a blind playthrough where I explored around quite a bit and had to take several minutes for some of the puzzles), but there are several different environments/levels and overall the game does feel like a ""complete"" game.Graphically, the game isn't triple-A quality but is still reasonably decent. Overall, I'd say the graphics are on par with the average games' graphics from 2010-2012.The story is fairly simple and straightforward, on par with a Lovecraft short story. You play as a standard faceless silent protagonist, and there's no real voice acting in the game, with the story being revealed through readable notes scattered throughout the game (the notes are generally in obvious locations and you don't have to explore hidden areas to find them). Overall the game is more about the atmosphere rather than the plot.Gamplay is a mixture of exploration, steath/evasion, and puzzle solving. The puzzles are decent and not too difficult; I never got stuck trying to figure out how to complete a puzzle, although there were a few times I did get stuck trying to progress because of other reasons (finding the switch for the hidden door in the Egyptian area is the example that most comes to mind).Item-hunting is minimum as the game doesn't really have an inventory or item system. The only items found in the environment are key items, notes that give snippets of the story, and batteries to instantly recharge your flashlight to 100% (the flashlight also slowly recharges when not in use, so you won't get stuck if you can't find a battery).Like Amnesia, the game has monsters you need to stealth around or run away from. The monsters patrol along a fixed route, have a visual detection range of about 20-30 feet, respond to noise (i.e. running fast) as well as if you shine the flashlight on them. There's only one monster type and graphically they don't look great up close, but are decent and unlike some other games are at least not Playstation 1 quality models. Their A.I. is quite simple, but functional.The monsters actually appear fairly sparingly; there are only 9-10 of them in the entire game. They're mostly to create the possibility of a threat instead of serving as a constant, ever-present threat (the monsters are actually fairly scarce, but the fact theycouldbe anywhere are what creates tension as you move through the environments). I actually appreciated this as this allows them to create tension without becoming obnoxious or frustrating.I did feel that the Museum of the Supernatural setting of the game was under-utilized. For the most part, the museum setting (with creepy exhibits etc) was only really majorly used in the first 1/4th of the game, Later areas (which comprised most of the game) were a more generic backstage office area, a dark basement, and an underground area.The ending was rather abrupt, but if you read all the notes and take in mind the fact the game takes place just a few years prior to the outbreak of World War I, it may kind of make sense what the developers were trying to imply with the ending.Overall, I wouldn't say Astray was great, per-se, but it was a good, competently and solidly made, complete experience, especially when you consider the fact it was made by only two people on a minimum budget.  Overall, it's one of the rare first-person microbudget indie games on Steam that is a full legit game that actually does ""deserve"" to be sold on Steam for money, rather than being a glorified programming student project."
