,Recommended,329200,17378266,"Posted: 3 August, 2015",all,Atara,"This Indie production suceedes in building suspense and fear using atmosphere, silence, and space. The environments, although somewhat generic and lacking in variety, are nonetheless well-designed to instill a sense of vast openness and foreboding.  This feeling is built less on cheap jump scares than on a more deeply-rooted, Lovecraftian cosmic fear. Astray takes a very minimalist approach to sound design, which works well. Without any music, every footstep sounds menacingly loud, and the slightest breath sets the player immediately on edge.Overall, while Astray succedes in building an atmosphere of dread, it is somewhat lacking in story and overall content. The game itself is very short (most players should finish it in under 2 hours), partly due to the incredibly easy puzzles found in the first half of the game. The backstory builds slowly through various notes found throughout the environments. Although the writing is fine, the story is somewhat thin and, until the very end, fails to evoke much intrigue or mystery. Despite this, Astray ends on a very strong note, and it is certainly worth playing through to experience the conclusion.Overall, Astray is a great effort by a small, independent team and succedes in building atmosphere and fear. Although quite short, the game offers a suspenseful journey through some unique environments, and is well worth the play through."
,Recommended,329200,14972964,"Posted: 20 March, 2015",all,RAIZO,"""Short but sweet"" pretty much sums this game up.  For only $6.99 one wouldn't expect too much from a game and that's certainly what you get with Astray.  It only takes about 2 hrs to beat and it looks nice and plays well, though there is some 'glitching', namely in the form of clipping = a few times while randomly standing in place to read a note, or while simply walking through a room, I suddently dropped through the floor and died.  It's an autosave game and whenever you die you're pretty much right where you last left off, which is nice, so don't worry about the minor clipping issue.There is no inventory in Astary and you only need to find little more than a half dozen keys/items to complete it.  Besides the clipping issue, the only other odd problem this game suffers from is a pointless use of batteries for your flashlight -it recharges when not in use and yet the developers thought it necessary to place some stray batteries throughout the game, which really doesn't make sense (were they trying to bank on the success of similar/non-inventory games like Outlast, wherein batteries are paramount to your success in surviving).Anyhoo, that and the clipping issue are about the only negatives I can come up with for this game.  The music/sound design works well with the pseudo-creepy museum the game largely takes place in and the handful of puzzles can easily be solved within minutes.  It's not exactly scary but it does have a 'Lovecraftian' theme to it, which is always good in my opinion. I would have preferred to pay only $4.99 for this, but still, it's nice to see more budget priced games like this on Steam.  Astray is worth a look if you have the money and a couple hours to kill."
